{{wikipedia|lang=en}}

===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*lewk-}}
Borrowed from {{bor|en|la|lumen||light, an opening}}. Use as a unit was first adopted by French physicist [[w:André Blondel|André Blondel]] in 1894.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|en|/ˈluːmən/}}
* {{a|GA}} {{enPR|lo͞oʹmən}}, {{IPA|en|/ˈlumən/}}
* {{audio|en|en-uk-lumen.ogg|Audio (UK)}}
* {{rhymes|en|uːmən|s=2}}
* {{hyphenation|en|lu|men}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|s|lumina}}

# {{lb|en|physics}} In the [[International System of Units]], the [[derived unit]] of [[luminous flux]]; the light that is emitted in a [[solid angle]] of one [[steradian]] from a source of one [[candela]]. Symbol: [[lm]].
# {{lb|en|anatomy}} The cavity or channel within a tube or tubular organ.
# {{lb|en|botany}} The cavity bounded by a plant cell wall.
# {{lb|en|medicine}} The bore of a tube such as a hollow needle or [[catheter]].

====Derived terms====
